1. GIT-NATIVE. Git notes is the substrate. The tool must be as
   git-native as possible. If git can do it, we don't wrap it.

2. SKILL STAYS IN SYNC. SKILL.md reflects discovered best practices
   as we learn them. It cannot force agent behavior, but it shows
   what a good job looks like. Update the skill when patterns emerge.

3. PAVE THE DESIRE PATH (Steve Yegge). When agents hallucinate CLI
   paths or get errors, that is signal — our interface is not ergonomic
   to agents. Fix the interface, don't blame the agent.

4. SELF-DOCUMENTING CLI. help must be complete. Errors must be clear.
   An agent should never need to read source to use the tool.

5. TEST WITH REAL AGENTS. CLI changes must be tested in interactive
   agent sessions (tmux + pi/claude-code). Unit tests verify mechanics;
   agent tests verify ergonomics.

6. BASH AND GIT ONLY. No runtimes, no package managers, no build steps.
   jj+git colocation is on the roadmap but not now.

7. DOGFOOD. Use mycelium to develop mycelium. Every session should
   read notes on arrival and leave notes on departure.

8. BRANCH FOR FEATURES. New commands and behavioral changes develop
   on a jj bookmark + mycelium branch. Main stays stable.

   Workflow:
     jj new -m 'feature: description'
     jj bookmark set feature-name
     ./mycelium.sh branch use feature-name

   Work, test, leave notes on the branch. When tests pass and the
   feature is dogfooded:

     jj bookmark move master --to @
     ./mycelium.sh branch use main
     ./mycelium.sh branch merge feature-name

   Code and notes branch together, merge together. An agent arriving
   on main during development sees stable code and stable notes.
